<section xml:id="sec-geo-apps-of-cross-products" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Geometric applications of cross products</title>

 <p>
The formula
<me>
\|\vect{u} \times \vect{v}\| = \|\vect{u}\|\|\vect{v}\|\sin\theta
</me> 
has a geometric interpretation. From trigonometry, we know that if <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are 
two side lengths of a triangle, and <m>\theta</m> is the angle between these sides, then the area of the 
triangle is <m>\frac{1}{2}ab \sin\theta</m>. Therefore we can deduce the following corollary, which is 
illustrated in <xref ref="fig-cross_area"/>. 
</p>

<corollary xml:id="cor-area-of-parallelogram">
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>\vect{u}, \vect{v} \in \R^3</m>. Then <m>\|\vect{u}\times \vect{v}\|</m> is the area of the 
parallelogram inscribed by <m>\vect{u}</m> and <m>\vect{v}</m>, and 
<m>\frac{1}{2}\|\vect{u}\times \vect{v}\|</m> is the area of the triangle inscribed by 
<m>\vect{u}</m> and <m>\vect{v}</m>.
</p>
</statement>
</corollary>

<figure xml:id="fig-cross_area">
<caption>The area of this parallelogram is <m>\|\vect{u}\times \vect{v}\|</m>, which is twice the area of the triangles.</caption>
<!--cross_area.tikz-->
</figure>

<example xml:id="ex-area-of-triangle">
<statement>
<p>
Calculate the area of the triangle formed by the points <m>A = (1, 2, -1)</m>, <m>B = (2, 4, 1)</m>, 
<m>C = (0, 2, -2)</m>.
We have
<md>
<mrow>
\overrightarrow{AB} \amp  = [2, 4, 1] - [1, 2, -1] = [1, 2, 2]     \\
\overrightarrow{AC} \amp  = [0, 2, -2] - [1, 2, -1] = [-1, 0, -1]
</mrow>
</md>.
Thus <m>\overrightarrow{AB} \times \overrightarrow{AC} = [-2-0, -2+1, 0+2] = [-2, -1, 2]</m>, which has 
length <m>\sqrt{2^2 + 1 + 2^2} = \sqrt{9} = 3</m>. So the area of the triangle is
<me>
\frac{1}{2}\|\overrightarrow{AB}\times \overrightarrow{AC}\| = \frac{3}{2}.
</me>
</p>
</statement>
</example>


<remark xml:id="rem-parallelopiped">
<statement>
<p>
Three vectors <m>\vect{u},\mathbf{v},\mathbf{w}\in{\mathbb R}^3</m> inscribe a <term>parallelopiped</term>, as is illustarted in
<xref ref="fig-parallelopiped"/>. The volume of this shape is given by
<md>
  |\vect{u}\cdot(\vect{v}\times\vect{w})|
</md>.
The term <m>\vect{u}\cdot(\vect{v}\times\vect{w})</m> is called the <term>scalar triple product</term> of 
<m>\vect{u},\vect{v},\vect{w}\in {\mathbb R}^3</m>.
</p>
</statement>
</remark>

